ing to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Buckingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the former county seat of the county of Buckinghamshire, Old English <i>Buccingahamm</i> ‘water meadow (Old English <i>hamm</i>) of the people of (<i>-inga-</i>) <i>Bucc(a)</i>’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Advice","type":"FIRST","meanings":["See Hawise."],"variants":[{"name":"Avis","meanings":["From a Norman French form of the ancient Germanic name <i>Aveza</i>, derived from a short form of one or more compound names containing the first element <i>av</i> (as in   Ava ;  the meaning is uncertain). The correspondence in form to the Latin word <i>avis</i> ‘bird’ is coincidental."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Upton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places in England called Upton, most of which are named with Old English <i>upp</i> ‘upper’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some have different origins, such as one in Essex, originally named with the phrase <i>upp in tūne</i> ‘up in the settlement’, i.e. the higher part of the settlement, and Upton Lovell (Wiltshire), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Ubba</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>. This name was brought to Ireland (Antrim) in 1598 by Henry <i>Upton</i>, from Upton in Devon."],"variants":[{"name":"Uptain","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of English   Upton  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":10,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Advice of Upton Countess of Buckingham was born in 1445, in Buckinghamshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with John Stafford of Buckingham. She died in 1525, in her hometown, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1445–1525":"1445–1525","1445–1505":"1445–1505","1470–1540":"1470–1540","1525":"1525","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1540":"1540","1 January 1470":"1. jaanuar 1470","1470":"1470","1505":"1505","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Wing, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wing, Buckinghamshire, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1445–1525":"1445–1525","1445–1505":"1445–1505","1470–1540":"1470–1540","1525":"1525","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1540":"1540","1 January 1470":"1. tammikuuta 1470","1470":"1470","1505":"1505","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Wing, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wing, Buckinghamshire, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1445–1525":"1445–1525","1445–1505":"1445–1505","1470–1540":"1470–1540","1525":"1525","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1540":"1540","1 January 1470":"1 janvier 1470","1470":"1